'use strict';

/* ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   WATER SORT — potion-sorting puzzle ("Tränke")

   Bottles hold up to WS_CAPACITY stacked units of colored liquid.
   Pour rules: A→B legal only if B has room AND (B empty OR B's top
   color == A's top color); a pour always moves the full contiguous
   top-color run from A, capped by B's remaining space. Win when every
   bottle is empty or full+monochrome — a still-locked bottle (see below)
   never counts, regardless of its hidden contents.

   Only 1 free spare bottle per level, always — buying an extra one via
   wsBuyExtraBottle() (spends a quiz question) is meant to matter, not be a
   rarely-needed safety net.

   Two mechanics layer on top of the classic rules, introduced gradually
   across the level pool (see scripts/generate-ws-levels.js's difficulty
   table — early levels are classic-only):
   - Fog: some units start hidden ("?"), except a bottle's current top unit,
     which is always visible (you need it to judge legal pours). A unit
     that's ever been the top stays revealed permanently, even if a later
     pour covers it again — see wsRevealTops().
   - Locked bottles: fully inert (can't be poured into or out of) and
     covered, showing only a dot in the color they need. They unlock the
     moment that color is fully isolated into one pure bottle *elsewhere* on
     the board (the triggering bottle isn't consumed) — see wsCheckUnlocks().

   Levels are static data (WS_LEVELS below) rather than generated live in
   the browser. Earlier attempts at live seeded-PRNG generation (simulating
   legal pours starting from a solved state, then unscrambling) kept
   producing boards with an isolated color bottle left untouched — and
   therefore still solved on load — because once the spare bottles
   saturate, a randomly-touched color has nowhere left to go, so a specific
   color could go untouched indefinitely. Real per-level data sidesteps
   this: each entry was generated offline (scripts/generate-ws-levels.js)
   by dealing a genuinely shuffled deck of color units into bottles, then
   independently verified solvable (respecting locked-bottle rules) via
   repeated randomized playouts before being accepted — see that script for
   the full generation/verification process. Only the shuffled play order,
   position in it, and the live in-progress bottle state are persisted in
   the save; the level layouts themselves ship with the app.
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ */

